excerpt: Medieval basilica with relics of 128 saints & a thorn said to have come from the Crown of Thorns.
detail_description: Basilique Saint-Sernin de Toulouse, a medieval basilica located in Toulouse, France, is renowned for housing relics of 128 saints and a thorn believed to be from the Crown of Thorns. This UNESCO-listed site is one of the largest Romanesque churches in Europe. The church's crypt contains an extensive collection of relics donated by Charlemagne to the abbey on this site in the 800s.
name: Basilique Saint-Sernin de Toulouse
address: Basilica of St. Sernin, 7 Pl. Saint-Sernin, 31000 Toulouse, France

excerpt: Space-themed attraction with exhibits, an IMAX cinema, a planetarium & an interactive kids' section.
detail_description: Cité de l'Espace is a futuristic theme park and museum in Toulouse that offers an interactive experience for space enthusiasts of all ages. Visitors can explore exhibits, watch IMAX films, and gaze at the giant Ariane space rocket. The museum also features a playground called the Little Astronaut for kids to enjoy while adults tour the Mir Space station. This space-themed attraction provides an educational and entertaining experience for families, making it a must-visit site in Toulouse.
name: Cité de l'Espace

excerpt: Natural history museum with permanent & temporary exhibitions, kids' activities & botanical gardens.
detail_description: Muséum de Toulouse is a captivating natural history museum in Toulouse, offering an extensive collection of over 2.5 million artifacts spread across 3,000 square meters. Founded in 1796 by naturalist Philippe-Isidore Picot de Lapeyrouse, the museum aims to educate the public through its five themed permanent exhibitions covering topics such as Earth's early history, the nature of life, and the future of mankind.
name: Muséum de Toulouse

excerpt: Fine art museum particularly rich in sculpture, including a unique collection of Romanesque works.
detail_description: The Musée des Augustins, located in Toulouse, is a fine art museum housed in an old Augustinian monastery. Since 1793, it has been home to numerous works of art, including Romanesque sculptures and paintings from the 17th and 19th centuries. Notable pieces include 'Christ between Two Thieves' by Rubens and 'The Descent from the Cross' by local artist Nicolas Tournier.
name: Musée des Augustins

excerpt: Medieval building for antiquities museum with Roman sculptures, local archaeological finds & garden.
detail_description: Musee Saint-Raymond is a medieval building in Toulouse, France that houses an impressive collection of Roman sculptures, local archaeological finds, and a charming garden. The museum offers a diverse range of artifacts dating back to prehistoric and BC eras, as well as exhibits from ancient history and the Middle Ages. Visitors can also explore unique art pieces and handicraft works within its walls.
name: Musée Saint-Raymond

excerpt: Striking Dominican edifice housing Thomas Aquinas' tomb & known for its Gothic vaults.
detail_description: The Couvent des Jacobins is a remarkable Dominican edifice in Toulouse, known for its Gothic architecture and as the final resting place of Saint Thomas Aquinas. The Eglise des Jacobins boasts ornate stained-glass windows, while the Cloitre des Jacobins features graceful russet-brick columns surrounding a green courtyard.
name: Couvent des Jacobins

excerpt: Artworks by global artists dating from after WWII, with regular exhibitions, plus a cafe & bookshop.
detail_description: Les Abattoirs is a contemporary art museum located in Toulouse, housed in a former 19th-century industrial building that was once a slaughterhouse. The museum's collection boasts over 2,000 artworks including paintings, sculptures, prints, drawings, photos and installations by renowned artists such as Saura, Tapies, Fontana, Rauschenberg and Duchamp.
name: Les Abattoirs
address: 76 All. Charles de Fitte, 31300 Toulouse, France

detail_description: Pont Neuf, also known as the New Bridge, is a popular spot in Toulouse, France. Despite its name, it's actually the oldest bridge in the city, dating back to the 16th century. Situated on the Garonne River, it offers picturesque views and is a favorite photography location for visitors. For the best vantage point, head to the left bank of the river to capture stunning images of this historic landmark.
name: Pont Neuf

detail_description: When in Toulouse, don't miss the iconic Place du Capitole. This grand central square is dominated by a magnificent neoclassical palace adorned with intricate frescoes. The palace, known as the Capitole, serves as the city hall and is also home to the Theatre du Capitole de Toulouse opera company and the Orchestre national du Capitole de Toulouse.
name: Place du Capitole

excerpt: Free tours of majestic neoclassical palace housing lavish ceremonial rooms painted with frescoes.
detail_description: Place du Capitole is a must-visit attraction in Toulouse, featuring a majestic neoclassical palace that houses lavish ceremonial rooms adorned with frescoes. The square dates back to the 1100s and is located right in front of the city hall. Visitors can relax at charming cafes while admiring the beauty of Toulouse's Capitole or explore the palace to see historical paintings and artworks.
name: Place du Capitole
address: JC3V+P8, 1 Rue Ernest Roschach, 31000 Toulouse, France

excerpt: Toulouse, capital of France’s southern Occitanie region, is bisected by the Garonne River and sits near the Spanish border. It’s known as La Ville Rose (‘The Pink City’) due to the terra-cotta bricks used in many of its buildings. Its 17th-century Canal du Midi links the Garonne to the Mediterranean Sea, and can be traveled by boat, bike or on foot.
detail_description: Toulouse, the capital of France's Occitanie region, is known as La Ville Rose (The Pink City) due to its distinctive terra-cotta brick buildings. The city is bisected by the Garonne River and boasts the 17th-century Canal du Midi, offering opportunities for boat rides, cycling, and leisurely walks. Visitors can explore a variety of shops offering violet-themed souvenirs and gastronomic delights such as pate or confit de canard.
name: Toulouse

excerpt: Historic covered market with many stalls selling premium fish, meats, cheeses & other foodstuffs.
detail_description: The Victor Hugo Market in Toulouse is a historic covered market with 88 stalls offering premium fish, meats, cheeses, and other foodstuffs. It's a foodie paradise featuring specialty vendors like Maison Garcia for sausages and foie gras, Chez Betty for cheese, and Busquets for artisan chocolates. The upper floor hosts five restaurants while the market's watering holes like Electro Bar and Bar des Amis offer drinks to accompany your purchases.
name: Victor Hugo Market

excerpt: Landscaped Japanese garden with a pond crossed by a small red bridge overlooked by a tea pavilion.
detail_description: Pierre-Baudis Japanese Garden, nestled in the heart of Toulouse, offers a serene escape with its meticulously designed landscape. This tranquil oasis celebrates the bond between Toulouse and Kyoto, featuring traditional elements like a tea pavilion, stone lanterns, and a koi pond. Visitors can wander along winding paths, admiring carefully pruned plants and finding moments of zen amidst the urban bustle.
name: Pierre-Baudis Japanese Garden
address: Jardin Compans Caffarelli, Bd Lascrosses, 31000 Toulouse, France

excerpt: The historic heart of the city, elegant Capitole de Toulouse fans out from the vast Place du Capitole and its Théâtre du Capitole opera house. Notre Dame de la Daurade basilica has Roman origins, while Couvent des Jacobins is known for its graceful cloister. The Bemberg Foundation’s huge art collection is housed in the Hotel d’Assézat Renaissance mansion. Gascon bistros serving regional cuisine line medieval alleys.
detail_description: Capitole de Toulouse is the historic heart of the city, centered around the vast Place du Capitole and its Théâtre du Capitole opera house. The area features notable landmarks such as Notre Dame de la Daurade basilica with Roman origins, Couvent des Jacobins known for its graceful cloister, and the Bemberg Foundation’s extensive art collection housed in the Hotel d’Assézat Renaissance mansion.
name: Capitole de Toulouse

excerpt: 19th-century museum displaying Asian art & Egyptian antiquities, with a library & botanic gardens.
detail_description: The Georges Labit Museum, also known as Musee Georges Labit, is a captivating 19th-century museum located in Toulouse. It was established by Georges Labit to showcase his extensive collection of treasures from the Far East and Ancient Egypt. The museum is housed in a magnificent Moorish villa near the Canal du Midi, designed by architect Jules Calbayrac. Visitors can explore various themed rooms dedicated to cultures such as Egypt, Japan, China, India, and Mongolia.
name: Georges Labit Museum

excerpt: Showcase for a company that makes massive, fantasy-themed automatons, with daily demonstrations.
detail_description: La Halle de la Machine in Toulouse is a whimsical wonderland where fantasy comes to life through colossal automatons. Nestled in the Montaudran district, this unique venue showcases incredible creations like the towering animatronic Minotaur Asterion and its gigantic spider companion, Ariane. Visitors can enjoy daily demonstrations that include an eclectic orchestra made from recycled materials, featuring everything from old klaxons to abandoned guitars transformed into musical instruments.
name: Halle de la Machine
address: 3 Av. de l'Aérodrome de Montaudran, 31400 Toulouse, France

detail_description: Toulouse is a city with a rich musical heritage, offering a diverse range of music experiences. The Théâtre du Capitole stands as an iconic landmark in the city, housing both the town hall and the opera house behind its pink neoclassical facade. The venue hosts classical music performances and operas, making it a must-visit for music enthusiasts.
name: Théâtre du Capitole

excerpt: Elegant 1555 mansion housing 5 centuries of European art from the Renaissance to the 19th century.
detail_description: Georges Bemberg’s Foundation, also known as the Hotel of Assézat, is a must-visit in Toulouse. Housed in an elegant 16th-century mansion, it showcases a remarkable collection of European art spanning five centuries. The museum features restored rooms that exude 19th-century grandeur and display an impressive array of paintings, furniture, and ornaments by renowned artists such as Degas, Monet, Matisse, and Boudin.
name: Georges Bemberg’s Foundation — Hotel of Assézat

detail_description: Stade Toulousain, based in Toulouse, is a prominent rugby union team with a rich history of success. The club has contributed numerous players to the French national team and holds the record for the most Heineken Cup trophies. Additionally, they have secured 19 French Championships, making them a dominant force in domestic competitions. Visitors can catch an exhilarating game at Stade Ernest-Wallon between August and May.
name: Stade Toulousain

excerpt: Shaded riverside meadows & picnic spot with a summer beach area, playground, bar & city views.
detail_description: Prairie des Filtres is a beloved public garden in Toulouse, offering stunning views of the Jarun River and providing an ideal location for relaxation. The park features leafy trees, vast green areas, and picturesque paths for leisurely strolls. Visitors can enjoy picnics, take in the city views, and partake in various activities such as the Rio Loco music festival and Toulouse Plages during the summer months.
name: Prairie des Filtres

detail_description: Jardin Japonais Joseph in Toulouse is a serene spot for a morning stroll, spanning 7000 square meters. It embodies the essence of a traditional Japanese garden with its characteristic rocks, water features, and pavilion. The garden also boasts a tranquil zen rock garden and lush bamboo groves, creating an idyllic setting for relaxation and contemplation.
name: Jardin Japonais Joseph

detail_description: Quai de la Daurade is a picturesque riverside promenade in the heart of Toulouse, offering stunning views of the Garonne River and the city skyline. It's a favorite spot for both locals and visitors to gather and enjoy the spectacular sunset over the river. The area is adorned with benches and grassy areas, creating a perfect setting for an evening filled with relaxation and natural beauty.
name: Quai de la Daurade

detail_description: Place Saint-Pierre in Toulouse is a hotspot for sports fans, especially rugby enthusiasts. The riverside area is lined with bars where people gather to watch matches. Chez Tonton and Le Filochard are popular spots known for their lively atmosphere and good drinks. The square also features a vintage carousel in front of Square Louise Michel, making it a picturesque location for photos with the Sacre-Coeur in the background.
name: Place Saint-Pierre

detail_description: Canal de Brienne is a picturesque waterway in the heart of Toulouse, France. Built in 1776, it stretches for 1.6 kilometers and provides a peaceful setting for leisurely strolls along its tree-lined paths. The canal connects to the Garonne River and features operational twin locks that add to its charm.
name: Canal de Brienne

excerpt: Collections of paintings, drawings, carvings, jewelery, watches & coins in a restored hotel.
detail_description: The Musée Paul-Dupuy, located in Toulouse, France, is a captivating destination for art and history enthusiasts. Housed in a restored hotel, the museum showcases an extensive collection of paintings, sculptures, decorative arts, historical objects, jewelry, watches and coins. Originally a private museum acquired by the renowned art collector Paul Dupuy and later gifted to the city of Toulouse in the early 20th century, it now offers visitors a diverse array of artworks spanning different periods and styles.
name: Musée Paul-Dupuy
address: 13 Rue de la Pleau, 31000 Toulouse, France

detail_description: Pl. de la Daurade is located in a trendy area, nestled between the Capitol and Place de la Daurade. It's an ideal spot to relax and soak in the atmosphere. COUTUME, a renowned coffee roaster from Paris, has set up shop here, offering espresso made with naturally processed beans from the Mengalli family farm in Vale dos Italianos, Divinolandia, Brazil.
name: Pl. de la Daurade

detail_description: Les Abattoirs, once a slaughterhouse, has been transformed into a vibrant modern art museum. This cultural hub hosts a variety of performances, events, and concerts in addition to its impressive collection of contemporary artworks.
name: Les Abattoirs

excerpt: Medieval cathedral made of two churches in distinct Roman & Gothic architectural styles.
detail_description: Saint Stephen's Cathedral, also known as Saint-Etienne Cathedral, is a medieval masterpiece located in Toulouse. This architectural wonder is a combination of Roman and Gothic styles, with elements of Baroque and Romanesque architecture. The cathedral's construction spanned over five centuries, resulting in a unique blend of diverse architectural influences that some find perplexing yet captivating.
name: Saint-Etienne Cathedral

detail_description: The Chapelle des Carmélites in Toulouse is a stunning single-room chapel constructed in 1622, and it's the only remaining part of a larger Carmelite convent. The vaulted ceiling with oak paneling, hanging keystones, and murals inspired by the Sistine Chapel paintings make this baroque structure a must-see gem reminiscent of its famous counterpart. Located on Rue du Perigord, this small chapel is often compared to the Sistine Chapel for its sublime painted ceilings.
name: Chapelle des Carmélites

excerpt: Public park & 18th-century botanic gardens with a pond, playground & medicinal plant collection.
detail_description: Jardin des Plantes is a renowned public park and 18th-century botanic garden in Toulouse. It's a popular free attraction offering visitors the chance to enjoy its lush green spaces, captivating water ponds, and medicinal plant collection. The park spans seven hectares and is located near the Canal de Midi, featuring an array of species including Japanese cypresses. Visitors can stroll through pathways adorned with statues and relax by a charming waterfall.
name: Jardin des Plantes

excerpt: Stone road bridge with 7 arches completed in 1632 spanning the Garonne river & stretching 722 feet.
detail_description: Pont Neuf is a historic stone road bridge in Toulouse, completed in 1632, spanning the Garonne river with its seven arches and stretching 722 feet. It's a popular spot for wedding photos due to its romantic setting with the Garonne flowing beneath and the historical architecture providing a picturesque backdrop. The bridge took nearly 90 years to complete, replacing two older bridges that linked the banks of the river.
name: Pont Neuf

excerpt: Venue used mainly for soccer & rugby matches, including those of Toulouse Football Club.
name: Stadium de Toulouse

excerpt: Palace built in the early 1500s featuring Renaissance & Gothic architecture & a tall tower.
detail_description: Hôtel de Bernuy, a palace constructed in the early 1500s, showcases a blend of Renaissance and Gothic architecture along with a towering structure. This historic site is part of the legacy left by pastel merchants and now houses Pierre de Fermat college. Visitors can explore its well-preserved courtyards on guided tours offered by the tourism office.
name: Hôtel de Bernuy

detail_description: The Hôtel du Vieux-Raisin is a beautiful private mansion from the golden age of Pastel in Toulouse. It is an essential passage when visiting this city, as it showcases the enrichment of certain families during that time.
name: Hôtel du Vieux-Raisin

detail_description: Pierre Hotel, also known as Hôtel de Clary, is a beautiful hotel located in the heart of Toulouse. It has an astonishing facade in relation to the architecture of the monuments that surround it and is well worth a visit.
name: Hôtel de Clary / Hôtel de Pierre
address: 25 Rue de la Dalbade, 31000 Toulouse, France

detail_description: Located on a historic site in Toulouse, "L'Envol des Pionniers" offers an immersive experience into the fascinating world of aeronautics and the history of Aeropostale. The museum showcases a wide array of objects from the early days of aviation and provides interactive explanations about the evolution of airlines over the years. Visitors can also explore a room dedicated to Antoine de Saint-Exupery and his desert adventures.
name: L'Envol des Pionniers

detail_description: When visiting Toulouse, don't miss the chance to explore the renowned Airbus headquarters and its on-site museum, JL Lagardere Airbus factory. You can take a tour of the working factory and learn about their impressive aircraft like A330neo, A350XWB, and A380. The city also offers other attractions such as Lac de Saint Caprais, Musee Aeroscopia, LE LOFT, Toulouse Pont Neuf, and Basilique St-Sernin.
name: Airbus
address: Airbus M01, Chem. de l'Espeissière M30, 31300 Toulouse, France

excerpt: Elegant 1555 mansion housing 5 centuries of European art from the Renaissance to the 19th century.
detail_description: Fondation Bemberg is a remarkable museum located in the opulent Renaissance-era Hotel d'Assezat on Rue de Metz. The hotel was constructed in the 16th century for Capitoul Pierre d'Assezat, who amassed wealth from plant dye production. One of its distinctive architectural elements is the courtyard adorned with intricate sculptural details and arcaded loggia. Although temporarily closed to the public, it's eagerly anticipated to reopen soon.
name: Georges Bemberg’s Foundation — Hotel of Assézat

detail_description: Le Capitole, located in the heart of Toulouse since the 12th century, is a symbol of the city's evolution. Initially constructed as a seat of government, it has undergone a 500-year architectural transformation. The building houses both the town hall and the Theatre du Capitole and features state rooms including the impressive Salle des Illustres. Le Capitole is situated across from Place du Capitole and offers a rich historical experience with influences from the Roman Empire.
name: Le Capitole

detail_description: Canal du Midi is a significant waterway in Toulouse, connecting the city to Sete. The canal is popular among cyclists and offers a picturesque route for biking trips. It is also praised as an excellent location for walking and running, providing a peaceful and historically rich environment. Toulouse itself boasts attractions such as the Basilique Saint-Sernin, Place du Capitol, Cite de lEspace theme park, and Japanese Gardens.
name: Canal du Midi

detail_description: The Sauvages à Histoires Botanical Garden is currently under construction, promising an exciting new experience for visitors in the near future.
name: sauvages à histoires Botanical Garden
address: 76 All. Charles de Fitte, 31300 Toulouse, France

detail_description: The Salle des Illustres, located in the Capitole building, is a grand reception room that overlooks the Place du Capitole. It serves as a space for distinguished guests to greet crowds and for Stade Toulousain to present trophies to supporters. The interior is adorned with 19th-century paintings and sculptures depicting key moments and emblematic characters from the city's history.
name: Salle des Illustres

detail_description: Located in the heart of Toulouse, Jardin des Plantes is a historic botanical garden established in the 18th century. It offers a peaceful retreat with beautifully curated plant collections and educational activities focusing on biodiversity and conservation. The verdant oasis features duck ponds, playgrounds, and shaded pathways, making it an ideal spot for picnics and relaxation.
name: Jardin des Plantes

excerpt: This historic park includes a fountain, gazebo & flower gardens, plus sculptures, bridges & benches.
detail_description: Grand Rond Park, one of the most renowned parks in Toulouse, is a historic site featuring a fountain, gazebo, flower gardens, sculptures, bridges and benches. Spanning over four hectares and constructed in the mid-1700s as part of urban development efforts in Toulouse, this park is named after the Bowling Green lawn used for playing boules. It offers appealing green spaces with thick trees and alluring water ponds.
name: Grand Rond

excerpt: Basilica with origins in a Roman temple, housing an 1807 copy of a 15th-century Black Madonna.
detail_description: The Basilica of Our Lady of the Daurade, located in Toulouse, has a rich history dating back to a Roman temple. It is home to an 1807 replica of the 15th-century Black Madonna. Situated by the Garonne River, it offers a serene atmosphere and houses the Black Madonna adorned in exquisite garments designed by renowned fashion designers.
name: Basilique Notre-Dame de la Daurade
address: 1 Pl. de la Daurade, 31000 Toulouse, France

detail_description: Église Notre-Dame de la Dalbade in Toulouse is a 15th-century Catholic church known for its stunning entrance facade featuring the Virgin Mary. The church boasts a captivating blend of Italian Renaissance and Gothic styles, along with exquisite ceramics crafted by Gaston Virebent in 1878. Its bell tower, once among the tallest structures in Toulouse at 91 meters, adds to its grandeur.
name: Église Notre-Dame de la Dalbade de Toulouse
address: 30 Rue de la Dalbade, 31000 Toulouse, France

excerpt: Landscaped park featuring tree-shaded benches, paved walkways, grassy lawns, statues & more.
detail_description: Jardin Compans-Caffarelli is a charming landscaped park located in the business district of Toulouse. It features tree-shaded benches, paved walkways, grassy lawns, and statues. The park is home to the Pierre Baudis Japanese gardens, offering an exotic and serene atmosphere for relaxation and meditation. Visitors can enjoy a leisurely stroll through well-maintained paths and admire various plants.
name: Jardin Compans-Caffarelli
